ğŸ”¹ Variables & Data Types in C
ğŸ“Œ What are Variables?
A variable is a name given to a memory location that stores a value.

ğŸ”¹ Declaring a Variable in C
data_type variable_name;
int age;  // Declares an integer variable named 'age'
ğŸ”¹ Data Types in C
C has several built-in data types for storing different types of values.
DataType	     Size       	Example	Usage
int           	4B	        int a = 10;	Whole numbers (positive, negative, zero)
float         	4B	        float pi = 3.14;	Decimal numbers (up to 6 digits precision)
double	        8B	        double x = 3.1415926535;	Decimal numbers with higher precision
char	          1B        	char grade = 'A';	Stores single characters
void	          0B         	void function_name();	Used for functions that return nothing


ğŸ”¹ Example: Using Different Data Types
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int age = 20;
    float height = 5.9;
    double pi = 3.1415926535;
    char initial = 'A';

    printf("Age: %d\n", age);
    printf("Height: %.1f feet\n", height);
    printf("Value of Pi: %.10lf\n", pi);
    printf("Initial: %c\n", initial);

    return 0;
}


ğŸ”¹ Explanation
%d â†’ Used to print int values.
%f â†’ Used to print float values.
%.1f â†’ Prints float with 1 decimal place.
%lf â†’ Used to print double values.
%c â†’ Used to print characters.

